{
  "_schema": {
    "description": "Canonical Carcassonne base-game tile distribution: 24 tile types (ids A-X), 72 tiles total including 1 start tile. Pins deck composition AND per-tile field topology so every implementation works against an identical dataset. Field geometry is internally consistent and may not perfectly mirror the printed tiles; that is acceptable by design.",
    "edges": "n/e/s/w, each 'city' | 'road' | 'field'. A single reference orientation; the engine applies 0/90/180/270 rotation, permuting edges, city segments, road segments, and field positions together.",
    "fieldPositions": "Each tile border is divided into 8 field positions, two per edge, split where a road would cross. Clockwise from top-left: NW,NE (north), EN,ES (east), SE,SW (south), WS,WN (west). Positions on a city edge are city, not field, and never appear in a field region.",
    "cities": "City segments on the tile. Each has a stable id (c0, c1...), the edges it occupies, and a pennant flag (+2 in a completed city, +1 incomplete). Two segments on one tile are NOT connected (e.g. H, I).",
    "roads": "Road segments as lists of edges. A 2-edge segment is a through road (straight if opposite edges, curved if adjacent). A 1-edge segment terminates inside the tile at a junction hub, city wall, or cloister.",
    "fields": "Field regions on the tile. Each lists the field positions it covers and the ids of the city segments it borders (this adjacency drives farmer scoring). Across rotation, positions rotate with the tile.",
    "cloister": "true if the tile has a monastery at its centre.",
    "count": "Copies of this tile type in the 72-tile deck.",
    "startTile": "One copy of tile D is the start tile, placed at the origin before play; the remaining 71 are shuffled. D's count of 4 includes that start copy."
  },
